WEBVTT

00:20.662 --> 00:23.053
<i>The Red Sox are taking on</i>
<i>the Yankees at Fenway Park.</i>

00:23.088 --> 00:24.395
Five stars.

01:01.236 --> 01:02.268
Hmm.

01:42.805 --> 01:44.310
Oh.

01:44.345 --> 01:45.905
<i>Boston police.</i>

01:45.940 --> 01:48.743
Hi, this is I. M. Fletcher
calling from 5 Union Park.

01:48.778 --> 01:51.911
-<i> Yeah, and?</i>
-There's a murdered
woman downstairs.

01:51.946 --> 01:54.012
<i>-There's a what woman?</i>
-Murdered.

01:54.047 --> 01:56.982
<i> Well, uh,</i>
<i>this is just</i>
<i>a general precinct line.</i>

01:57.017 --> 01:58.852
<i>If you're scheduling a meeting</i>
<i>or something like that.</i>

01:58.887 --> 02:00.656
Yeah, well,
this is just a courtesy call.

02:00.691 --> 02:03.758
<i> A courtesy call?</i>
<i>You got a murder, you call 911.</i>

02:03.793 --> 02:08.059
Well...
...the emergency part's
kind of over, you know?

02:08.094 --> 02:10.336
<i> Well, this isn't</i>
<i>the murder department.</i>

02:11.405 --> 02:14.604
Can you just tell homicide?
It's 5 Union Park.

02:14.639 --> 02:16.672
They like murders.
They'll be interested.

02:26.486 --> 02:28.178
Uh, whoops.

02:31.183 --> 02:33.150
-You Fletcher?
-Yes.

02:33.185 --> 02:35.152
I'm Sergeant Inspector Monroe.

02:35.187 --> 02:37.594
Inspector?
Like in Scotland Yard?

02:37.629 --> 02:39.926
-This is Griz.
-Hello, Mr. Fletcher.

02:39.961 --> 02:41.829
Please,
my mother calls me Mr. Fletcher.

02:41.864 --> 02:43.897
-You can call me Fletch.
-Did you have a piece of fruit?

02:44.900 --> 02:46.471
I had a pear. How did you know?

02:46.506 --> 02:48.704
There's obviously
a piece missing.

02:48.739 --> 02:50.541
Griz, check the front door.

02:50.576 --> 02:51.971
Okay.

02:52.006 --> 02:54.611
-What's your full name?
-I. M. Fletcher.

02:54.646 --> 02:56.547
Hmm. I am Monroe.

02:57.583 --> 02:58.912
Full name, please.

03:00.487 --> 03:03.290
Irwin Maurice Fletcher.

03:11.729 --> 03:13.399
They caught me
in the middle of a yawn.

03:13.434 --> 03:15.093
They wouldn't let me retake it.
Can you imagine that?

03:16.162 --> 03:17.469
What'd you hit her with?

03:17.504 --> 03:18.998
I didn't hit her with anything.

03:19.033 --> 03:20.538
This your place?

03:20.573 --> 03:22.375
Well, I'm renting it
for a couple of weeks.

03:22.410 --> 03:24.707
-It's owned by a guy
named Owen Tasserly.

03:24.742 --> 03:27.281
Rather opulent
for just one person.

03:27.316 --> 03:31.043
Well, before you get the idea
that I'm some rich asshole,
I'm not.

03:31.078 --> 03:33.782
My girlfriend has the money.
She arranged this.

03:33.817 --> 03:35.586
Where is she?
Rome.

03:35.621 --> 03:37.390
Where I just flew back in from.

03:37.425 --> 03:39.051
Um,
I checked the front entrance.

03:39.086 --> 03:41.251
There's a key deadlock
and there's a sliding bolt

03:41.286 --> 03:43.726
and no footprints
and no forced entry.

03:43.761 --> 03:45.728
Nice job, Griz. Take five.

03:45.763 --> 03:47.059
What's your girlfriend's name?

03:47.094 --> 03:49.028
Andy. Angela.

03:49.063 --> 03:52.097
Andy Angela.
Write that down, Griz.

03:52.132 --> 03:54.605
It's Angela de Grassi.
You kill her too?

03:54.640 --> 03:57.234
May I remind you
that I reported this murder

03:57.269 --> 03:59.104
and waited
for you all to arrive?

03:59.139 --> 04:00.578
You been drinking long?
Oh, geez,

04:00.613 --> 04:02.349
I had my first beer
when I was 12.

04:03.550 --> 04:04.714
Mmm.

04:05.783 --> 04:07.277
Here you go, Griz.

04:07.312 --> 04:09.422
I'm not your waitress.

04:09.457 --> 04:11.952
No, I understand that,
but I thought maybe
you'd like my fingerprints.

04:11.987 --> 04:14.922
-See? Cooperating.
-Mmm.

04:14.957 --> 04:17.562
Hey, um, guy--
Sorry, I don't know your name.
Evidence?

04:20.028 --> 04:21.192
Do you need a blanket?

04:21.227 --> 04:22.732
You know what, Griz?

04:22.767 --> 04:24.668
Why don't you ask
Mr. Fletcher some questions.

04:24.703 --> 04:27.165
You're gonna have
the trainee interrogate me?

04:27.200 --> 04:28.738
Go ahead, Griz.

04:29.477 --> 04:30.641
Go ahead, Griz.

04:31.237 --> 04:33.314
Okay. Um...

04:36.847 --> 04:39.650
Um...
...Mr. Fletcher,

04:39.685 --> 04:42.279
did you know the victim,
Laurel Goodwin?

04:42.314 --> 04:44.985
Mm-mmm.
We never offer up
the victim's name.

04:45.020 --> 04:47.460
It's Griz's turn.

04:47.495 --> 04:49.891
Never met her. At least
not while she was alive.

04:49.926 --> 04:51.596
What flight were you on?
Alitalia.

04:51.631 --> 04:53.697
I landed at- 46 p.m.

04:53.732 --> 04:55.963
But you didn't call
the police until- 09.

04:55.998 --> 04:58.999
Well, I stopped and had dinner
at the Warren Tavern
on the way in.

04:59.034 --> 05:01.639
Can you produce proof of that?
A receipt, perhaps?

05:01.674 --> 05:03.674
-I paid cash.

05:03.709 --> 05:05.676
What do you do for a living?
-I'm a freelance journalist.

05:05.711 --> 05:08.305
I've spent the last two years
traveling Europe
writing about art.

05:08.340 --> 05:10.648
Quite the art collection
Mr. Tasserly has.

05:10.683 --> 05:11.847
Yeah.

05:11.882 --> 05:13.651
Paul Klee out there.
A Degas horse.

05:13.686 --> 05:15.620
I saw a Warhol over there
by the fish tank.

05:15.655 --> 05:17.083
See, this is my theory.

05:17.118 --> 05:20.350
I think the victim
interrupted an art theft.

05:20.385 --> 05:23.397
The thief got spooked,
bonked her over the head
and then ran.

05:23.432 --> 05:25.223
No amateur sleuthing,
please.

05:25.258 --> 05:28.864
Listen, I used to be
a investigative reporter
of some repute.

05:28.899 --> 05:30.668
I could be very helpful
in this whole matter.

05:30.703 --> 05:32.263
I used to play the trumpet
in high school.

05:32.298 --> 05:34.507
I never offered advice
to Miles Davis.

05:34.542 --> 05:36.168
Shut up and talk.

05:36.203 --> 05:38.203
That's a very confusing
combination of commands.

05:38.238 --> 05:40.513
Mr. Fletcher,
why are you in Boston?

05:40.548 --> 05:44.517
I'm researching a book.
The definitive biography
of Edgar Arthur Tharp Jr.

05:44.552 --> 05:46.376
The cowboy painter.

05:46.411 --> 05:48.686
-You've heard of him.
-I prefer Remington.

05:48.721 --> 05:50.556
You would.

05:50.591 --> 05:52.888
Go on, Griz.
Okay. Where was I?

05:52.923 --> 05:57.387
Sorry, I'm so distracted
by Mr. Fletcher's feet.

05:57.422 --> 05:59.730
Come on, Griz.
Feet want to be free.

05:59.765 --> 06:01.864
I see you two
have been brainwashed
by the shoe lobby.

06:01.899 --> 06:04.328
My Go--
Okay, look, Mr. Fletcher.

06:04.363 --> 06:08.134
If you did kill
this young woman, a confession
would be appreciated.

06:08.169 --> 06:11.170
I have a baby at the house.
Do you have a baby
at your house?

06:11.205 --> 06:13.403
I really could use some sleep.

06:13.438 --> 06:16.516
Okay, Inspector,
you know there's such a thing
as paternity leave, right?

06:18.179 --> 06:20.949
So, you're a journalist,
traipsing all over Europe?

06:20.984 --> 06:23.589
-You really make a living
doing that?
-Yeah, I make a decent one.

06:23.624 --> 06:29.892
No secondary forms of income
from more unsavory lines
of work?

06:29.927 --> 06:33.027
Writing for in-flight magazines
is about as unsavory as it gets.

06:33.062 --> 06:36.866
You got some place you can stay?
We're gonna need 24 hours
to do a full sweep.

06:36.901 --> 06:38.571
I don't know. Right here's okay.

06:40.267 --> 06:42.971
Are you sure there's nothing
you're hiding from me,
Mr. Fletcher?

06:44.876 --> 06:47.976
Come on, Inspector.
I'm an open book.

08:25.746 --> 08:27.581
Mr. Fletcher?
Yes.

08:28.650 --> 08:30.650
Thank you for meeting me,
Miss de Grassi.

08:31.686 --> 08:33.477
Would you like something, sir?

08:33.512 --> 08:34.687
Uh, are you paying?

08:35.547 --> 08:36.920
A negroni, please.

08:36.955 --> 08:39.659
-Madame, another one?
-No, thank you.

08:39.694 --> 08:42.189
So, how is
the Count Clementi
Arbogastes de Grassi?

08:43.027 --> 08:45.060
My father is fine.

08:45.095 --> 08:49.196
But I don't understand
why he hired you to find
his stolen paintings.

08:49.231 --> 08:51.737
Who are you?
I'm a freelance journalist.

08:51.772 --> 08:55.499
Uh, your father liked a piece
I wrote about an art theft
at the Royal Museum in Brussels.

08:55.534 --> 08:57.743
My story helped the police
crack the case.

08:57.778 --> 08:59.910
Good for you,
but you're not a detective.

08:59.945 --> 09:02.682
No, but I was
an investigative reporter
of some repute.

09:02.717 --> 09:05.047
I don't do much
of that anymore.
Why?

09:05.082 --> 09:09.986
It's an occupation that's been
cheapened by the digital age,
like president.

09:10.021 --> 09:13.418
Well, I wasn't
at my father's villa
when the paintings were stolen,

09:13.453 --> 09:15.860
so I don't have
any new information.

09:15.895 --> 09:17.158
Well, that's okay. I do.

09:19.129 --> 09:22.328
You do? Tell me.

09:22.363 --> 09:24.869
There's an art dealer
in Boston named Ronald Horan.

09:24.904 --> 09:27.234
He's already sold
two of your father's
Renaissance paintings.

09:27.269 --> 09:31.106
-The Bellini and the Perugino.
-Are you serious?
H-How would he have them?

09:31.141 --> 09:32.745
Well, I have no idea.

09:32.780 --> 09:34.681
He might not even know
that they were stolen.

09:34.716 --> 09:37.277
Do you think he has
the other paintings?
All nine were taken.

09:37.312 --> 09:38.784
He very well might.

09:38.819 --> 09:42.051
The Picasso was appraised
at 20 million dollars.

09:42.086 --> 09:45.285
Well, that hardly
seems worth stealing.
<i>Grazia.</i>

09:45.320 --> 09:47.419
Excuse me, I changed my mind.
I'll have another.

09:50.358 --> 09:52.457
So,
what are you going to do now?

09:52.492 --> 09:54.624
Well, I'd thought I'd visit
Mr. Horan in Boston

09:54.659 --> 09:57.528
and see if he had any ties
to Rome or the black market
in the art world.

09:57.563 --> 10:00.168
How can I help,
Mr. Fletcher?

10:00.203 --> 10:02.071
You don't need to be so formal.

10:02.975 --> 10:04.304
What should I call you?

10:06.440 --> 10:08.044
All of my friends call me...

10:08.079 --> 10:09.573
Fletch!

10:20.124 --> 10:24.797
I want to swim in your eyes.

10:25.657 --> 10:27.668
Like a...

10:28.165 --> 10:30.968
...piss.

10:32.939 --> 10:34.334
Like a piss?

10:35.502 --> 10:38.140
No, like a<i> pisciata,</i>
like a pool.

10:40.947 --> 10:43.442
My Italian is very good.

10:43.477 --> 10:48.689
-No. No. No.

10:53.487 --> 10:56.257
So what do you know
about this Ronald Horan?

10:56.292 --> 11:00.459
On his Facebook page,
I found out he teaches
an art history class at Harvard.

11:00.494 --> 11:02.296
He's a member
of the Mayflower Yacht Club

11:02.331 --> 11:06.333
and he's really into EDM,
electronic dance music.

11:07.402 --> 11:09.435
Had his gallery broken into
in 2015.

11:09.470 --> 11:12.911
They stole
some Impressionist paintings,
um...

11:12.946 --> 11:14.880
I really haven't found
anything incriminating.

11:14.915 --> 11:18.213
Sometimes I wonder
i-if my father's new wife,

11:18.248 --> 11:20.644
the Countess de Grassi,
as she loves to call herself,

11:20.679 --> 11:23.680
if somehow she's involved.

11:23.715 --> 11:28.091
I don't trust her, Fletch,
and I know she married papa
for his money.

11:28.126 --> 11:30.225
Well, Andy,
that's pretty cynical.

11:31.459 --> 11:33.261
Well, maybe she married him
for love...

11:33.901 --> 11:35.065
of money.

11:39.841 --> 11:41.665
<i>How did you end up in Europe?</i>

11:41.700 --> 11:43.469
<i>Was it because of a woman?</i>

11:43.504 --> 11:47.176
Two actually.
My ex-wives said
they needed space,

11:47.211 --> 11:49.508
so I figured
6,000 miles is about right.

11:49.543 --> 11:53.380
Wow, how is it
that you were married twice?

11:54.284 --> 11:57.318
I am very easy
to fall in love with.

11:57.353 --> 12:01.751
I'm very good
at falling in love.
Not so good at choosing.

12:01.786 --> 12:05.799
How so?
Well, I've fallen in love
with married men,

12:05.834 --> 12:09.297
pathological liars,
two drug dealers

12:10.003 --> 12:12.399
and a pyromaniac.

12:12.434 --> 12:14.973
Well, now, see,
I'm only one or two
of those things.

12:19.540 --> 12:21.881
Your famine
creates traffic jams.

12:21.916 --> 12:23.542
Please, no more Italian.

12:24.743 --> 12:27.018
-Ignore it.
-Mm-hmm.

12:31.618 --> 12:32.683
Okay.

12:38.295 --> 12:41.967
We need to speak
to Madam Angela de Grassi.

12:42.002 --> 12:43.430
Has something happened
to my father?

12:43.465 --> 12:45.069
I'm afraid so.

12:45.104 --> 12:46.697
He has been kidnapped.

12:46.732 --> 12:49.568
All we know is that
it was three men with guns.

12:49.603 --> 12:52.912
They put your father into a car
and drove off.

12:52.947 --> 12:55.079
They put the priest
in the machine?

12:55.114 --> 12:57.576
Did they hurt him?
We don't think so.

12:57.611 --> 13:00.282
You don't
have to speak in English.

13:00.317 --> 13:02.119
My Italian is very good.

13:03.617 --> 13:05.386
We've kept it quiet so far.

13:05.421 --> 13:07.058
Was the Countess de Grassi
there?

13:07.093 --> 13:09.819
No, she's visiting her brother
in Milan.

13:09.854 --> 13:11.491
The kidnappers have already
named a ransom.

13:11.526 --> 13:13.130
I'll pay them
whatever they want.

13:13.165 --> 13:15.132
They don't want money.

13:15.167 --> 13:17.695
They want a painting
your father owns.

13:19.633 --> 13:20.698
A Picasso.

13:22.735 --> 13:24.207
That's very Italian.

13:28.807 --> 13:30.983
<i> Fletch, I can't sleep.</i>

13:31.018 --> 13:33.348
<i>-I miss you.</i>
-I miss you too.
I wish you were here.

13:33.383 --> 13:35.152
Do I hear people talking?

13:35.187 --> 13:37.319
<i> Uh, listen, Andy,</i>
<i>I need you to contact that site</i>

13:37.354 --> 13:39.618
<i>where you found</i>
<i>Tasserly's townhouse.</i>

13:39.653 --> 13:41.752
Is there
something wrong with it?
Well, kinda.

13:41.787 --> 13:45.195
Uh,
I found a dead woman downstairs.

13:46.330 --> 13:48.935
What?<i> Oddio santo!</i>

13:48.970 --> 13:51.905
Who-Who-Who was she?
Who killed her?

13:51.940 --> 13:54.171
Apparently,
her name is Laurel Goodwin.

13:54.206 --> 13:57.009
I have no idea who killed her,
but there is a detective here

13:57.044 --> 14:00.012
who seems very keen on the idea
of it being me.

14:00.047 --> 14:01.409
How could he think that?

14:01.444 --> 14:02.740
<i> I'm looking into it.</i>

14:02.775 --> 14:05.116
Please don't get involved, okay?

14:05.151 --> 14:08.152
<i> We have to focus</i>
<i>on finding out</i>
<i>if Horan has the Picasso.</i>

14:08.187 --> 14:09.516
<i>Okay?</i>
<i>We have to save my father.</i>

14:09.551 --> 14:11.023
No, we will. We will.

14:11.058 --> 14:12.992
Did you get the line of credit
set up at Lloyds?

14:13.027 --> 14:14.686
<i>Of course I did.</i>

14:14.721 --> 14:16.688
Fletch, the Countess is
going around Rome

14:16.723 --> 14:18.789
telling anyone who will listen

14:18.824 --> 14:22.199
that my father's
left her everything,
as if he's already dead.

14:22.234 --> 14:24.135
<i> Andy,</i>
<i>why don't you just come here?</i>

14:24.170 --> 14:28.040
That way, we can be together
while I sort out
this Horan situation

14:28.075 --> 14:30.108
and all this other stuff.

14:30.143 --> 14:34.178
I want to be with you, Fletch,
but not with my father
still missing.

14:34.213 --> 14:36.741
<i>And now this horrible thing</i>
<i>has happened to you.</i>

14:36.776 --> 14:39.920
Yeah, I think the horrible thing
happened to Laurel Goodwin.

14:44.916 --> 14:47.488
-Yeah, is this Julio?

14:47.523 --> 14:52.064
Hi, it's Mr. Fletcher.
I was calling about the used van
you had listed on Only Vans.

14:52.099 --> 14:54.561
Morris.
Oh, that's great, yeah.

14:54.596 --> 14:57.927
I will--
I'll see you this afternoon.
Excellent. Thanks.

15:04.012 --> 15:05.077
You sleep.

15:21.920 --> 15:23.491
You know what?
Right here's fine.

15:23.526 --> 15:25.757
What? I can't stop here.

15:25.792 --> 15:28.034
Understood.
Maybe you have something
up there I can vomit into?

15:34.504 --> 15:35.833
-Five stars.
-Bye.

15:49.057 --> 15:50.122
Oh, my...

15:52.324 --> 15:53.521
Where the fuck are we?

15:54.227 --> 15:55.292
Um...

15:57.197 --> 15:58.229
Five stars.

16:07.834 --> 16:09.603
<i> Hello?</i>
Ralph Locke for Mr.--

16:18.977 --> 16:21.285
In here.

16:24.048 --> 16:25.784
Mr. Horan.

16:25.819 --> 16:28.523
Well, wonderful
to finally meet you, Mr. Locke.

16:28.558 --> 16:29.920
Please, call me Ralph.

16:29.955 --> 16:31.955
Ah, I'm sorry,
I don't shake hands.

16:31.990 --> 16:33.396
Uh, since the pandemic?

16:33.431 --> 16:34.958
Since touch screens.

16:34.993 --> 16:37.730
Haven't had a cold in 20 years.
Please.

16:37.765 --> 16:39.270
There you have it.
Mm-hmm.

16:39.305 --> 16:40.898
Some interesting music
you were listening to.

16:40.933 --> 16:44.539
Yes, it gets the blood pumping
and the pulse pounding.

16:44.574 --> 16:46.673
I guess that's why
it sounds like a heart monitor.

16:46.708 --> 16:49.643
I apologize, Ralph,
I'm a little pressed for time.

16:49.678 --> 16:51.348
I teach
a summer school class
at Harvard.

16:51.383 --> 16:52.778
Oh, please, no worries.

16:58.423 --> 17:01.259
<i> Portrait of a Woman</i>
<i>With an Ermine Collar.</i>

17:01.294 --> 17:04.262
In this case,
Picasso's wife, Olga.

17:04.297 --> 17:06.627
He made several portraits
of Olga,

17:06.662 --> 17:10.862
but when you emailed me
about this one, I didn't
really believe it existed.

17:11.832 --> 17:14.734
But it does.
And I found the owner.

17:14.769 --> 17:16.208
Is he willing to sell?

17:16.243 --> 17:18.573
Uh, he's willing
to entertain an offer.

17:18.608 --> 17:21.378
What's his name?
Oh, he prefers
to remain anonymous,

17:21.413 --> 17:23.413
but he lives in New York City

17:23.448 --> 17:26.548
and I think I can get
the Picasso here by Saturday,
maybe even Friday.

17:26.583 --> 17:28.044
Well, that is terrific.

17:28.079 --> 17:31.586
There is also the question
of credit, Mr. Locke.

17:31.621 --> 17:33.951
Most of the people I deal with
I've known for years.

17:33.986 --> 17:38.021
Lloyds Bank of Canary Islands
should be able to establish
whatever credit you require.

17:38.056 --> 17:41.266
It's like I've known you
for years.

17:41.301 --> 17:45.798
Here is a simple boilerplate
contract for my services.

17:45.833 --> 17:47.734
-'Kay.
-Oh, please.

17:56.074 --> 17:59.548
-Okay.
That one goes here.

18:02.080 --> 18:03.189
Of course.

18:05.292 --> 18:07.226
Quite the collection
of impressionists
you have here.

18:07.261 --> 18:12.396
Mmm.
Pre-, post-, neo-.
All the best prefixes.

18:12.431 --> 18:15.630
I was robbed a few years ago,
so I don't keep anything
of value in the building.

18:15.665 --> 18:17.962
Those are reproductions.
That's how I introduce
my children.

18:19.163 --> 18:21.339
Oh, do you sail?
I do not.

18:21.374 --> 18:23.737
I have an aversion
to boat shoes.
Well, shoes in general,

18:23.772 --> 18:26.608
but boat shoes in particular.
I mean, is it a slipper
or is it a shoe?

